55:27.692 --> 55:29.558
-- <i>We definitely need</i> a <i>plan.</i>
-- <i>We need</i> a <i>plan.</i>

55:29.627 --> 55:31.618
Here's what we're gonna do --
we're gonna make a list

55:31.696 --> 55:34.165
of all the sports moments that
are potential plays of the year.

55:34.232 --> 55:35.290
Then we're gonna
list the pros,

55:35.366 --> 55:36.629
and then we're gonna
list the "cons."

55:36.701 --> 55:37.964
Why do women like
making lists?

55:38.036 --> 55:39.868
-- Women don't like making lists.
-- Yes, they do.

55:39.938 --> 55:42.566
They're never quite so happy as when
they're making themselves a little list.

55:42.640 --> 55:44.039
You ever think about
why you make lists?

55:44.108 --> 55:45.576
It's so I can
cross things off it.

55:45.643 --> 55:48.010
You ever think about why you've
got so much crap in your wallet?

55:48.079 --> 55:49.547
I save my receipts.

55:49.647 --> 55:51.308
You save fortunes
from Chinese restaurants.

55:51.349 --> 55:53.044
-- [Clears throat] Can we work now?
-- VVell, I think we should.

55:53.117 --> 55:55.449
But Natalie's gonna want to
list the pros and the cons.

55:55.520 --> 55:57.648
-- <i>Women's ice hockey.</i>
-- <i>You're kidding.</i>

55:57.722 --> 56:00.623
The U.S. women's team won the first
Olympic gold medal in ice hockey,

56:00.692 --> 56:02.626
<i>and there were over 4,000 fans
in the arena to see them do it.</i>

56:02.694 --> 56:05.493
<i>They beat a bunch of Slovakian
cocktail waitresses,</i>

56:05.563 --> 56:08.897
and there were over 4,000 people
at my cousin Jacob's bar mitzvah.

56:08.967 --> 56:10.435
[Laughs]
What do you got?

56:10.501 --> 56:11.662
Mark McGwire hits 70.

56:11.736 --> 56:13.397
It's a little obvious.

56:13.471 --> 56:15.439
Our goal isn't to be
cunning, is it?

56:15.506 --> 56:17.770
Can we keep this organized?
Pros and cons.

56:17.842 --> 56:20.334
Well, the pro is he broke
an unbreakable record,

56:20.411 --> 56:23.506
and the con is Kim likes
women's ice hockey.

56:23.581 --> 56:25.242
-- What's next? -- <i>Jeff</i> Gordon.
-- No.

56:25.316 --> 56:27.580
-- Why? -- 'Cause it's NASCAR,
and who gives a damn?

56:27.652 --> 56:30.178
-- <i>Who gives</i> a damn? -- <i>How
many people give</i> a <i>good damn?</i>

56:30.254 --> 56:32.518
Well, it's the world's
most popular sport,

56:32.590 --> 56:34.558
so probably more than 4,000.

56:34.626 --> 56:35.923
-- Next.
-- All right.

56:35.994 --> 56:37.894
Austrian skier Herman Maier.

56:37.962 --> 56:40.329
-- <i>Pros.</i> -- <i>He got up from one
of the most horrific accidents</i>

56:40.398 --> 56:42.765
in Olympic history and won the
gold medal two days later.

56:42.834 --> 56:44.893
-- Cons.
-- <i>It's downhill skiing.</i>

56:44.969 --> 56:47.131
-- <i>And?</i>
-- <i>Who gives</i> a <i>damn?</i>

56:51.542 --> 56:54.603
<i>It was very important to
my parents and to their parents</i>

56:54.679 --> 56:57.205
that I be the first in
my family to attend college.

56:57.281 --> 56:58.771
<i>But I can't imagine
that any of them</i>

56:58.850 --> 57:01.342
<i>would feel anything
but shame and humiliation</i>

57:01.419 --> 57:04.116
at the sight of me playing
football under that flag.

57:04.188 --> 57:06.156
<i>I wish no disrespect
to my school,</i>

57:06.224 --> 57:08.283
<i>my fellow students,
or my teammates.</i>

57:08.359 --> 57:10.418
I'll answer any questions
you have at this point.

57:10.495 --> 57:13.021
What do you think's
gonna happen to him?

57:13.097 --> 57:15.327
[TV volume decreases]

57:15.400 --> 57:18.267
I keep watching it
over and over.

57:18.336 --> 57:19.929
<i>I think it's all
I've done today.</i>

57:20.004 --> 57:21.995
Shepard will get picked up
by another team.

57:22.073 --> 57:23.063
I'd imagine.

57:23.141 --> 57:24.836
The thing is,
six of his teammates

57:24.909 --> 57:26.638
stepped down, too --
six of them --

57:26.711 --> 57:28.805
two of them white and
none of them starters.

57:28.880 --> 57:30.473
<i>They're the ones who are
gonna have some trouble.</i>

57:30.548 --> 57:32.038
What'd you come in
to tell me?

57:32.116 --> 57:33.743
I wrote the piece.

57:33.818 --> 57:35.582
I'll tell Luther to watch it.

57:35.653 --> 57:39.556
It takes the position the Confederate
flag is a symbol of a culture --

57:39.624 --> 57:42.025
a culture with a great tradition
of literature and art,

57:42.093 --> 57:45.222
-- music and architecture, great statesmen.
-- That's crap.

57:45.296 --> 57:47.924
-- So why are you telling me to write it?
-- I'm not telling you <i>to</i> do anything.

57:47.999 --> 57:49.228
I think we're all pretty
surprised

57:49.333 --> 57:51.267
you're not doing a commentary yourself.
What's going on?

57:51.302 --> 57:53.134
-- Nothing's going on.
-- What's going on, Isaac?

57:53.204 --> 57:54.968
[Sighs]

58:00.078 --> 58:02.513
I don't want to make
this into a big deal.

58:02.580 --> 58:04.070
You don't want to make
What into a big deal?

58:04.148 --> 58:06.378
Luther's been looking for
an opportunity to fire me.

58:07.318 --> 58:08.979
He has been for
about six months.

58:09.053 --> 58:11.317
-- Are you sure? 'Cause I
think you're wrong. -- No.

58:11.389 --> 58:13.187
-- <i>I'm not.</i> -- <i>He has</i> a <i>lot
of respect for you, Isaac,</i>

58:13.257 --> 58:15.316
and while I may not like
the guy, he's sure no idiot.

58:15.393 --> 58:17.828
I like my life right now.
I've never been happier.

58:17.895 --> 58:21.126
I used to pick fights with management
twice a day, just like you.

58:21.199 --> 58:23.634
<i>They wanted to fire me,
that was fine.</i>

58:23.701 --> 58:25.897
There was always someone
who wanted to hire me.

58:25.970 --> 58:27.438
That's not the way it is now.

58:27.505 --> 58:30.964
<i>Luther can hire someone
half my age to do my job.</i>

58:31.042 --> 58:34.876
I like my life right now,
and I'm proud of this show.

58:34.946 --> 58:36.880
I can't believe it.

58:36.948 --> 58:38.848
I come in here
with you talking about

58:38.916 --> 58:41.180
those six players who
stood by Roland Shepard,

58:41.252 --> 58:43.414
and you don't have the same respect
for the people who work for you?

58:44.889 --> 58:46.755
You don't think if Luther
ever showed you the door

58:46.824 --> 58:49.452
there wouldn't be about a hundred
people lined up right behind you?

58:49.527 --> 58:53.361
<i>There's something real bad going
on in Chattanooga, Isaac,</i>

58:53.431 --> 58:56.366
and Luther can fix it.
And you know it.

58:57.969 --> 59:00.836
Tell Dana to throw this one
out of the rundown.

59:00.905 --> 59:04.102
Tell her you're gonna do
a 2-minute editorial.

59:04.175 --> 59:05.336
Not this time.

59:06.911 --> 59:08.208
Okay.

59:08.279 --> 59:10.213
Yeah. Uh, Danny...

59:12.283 --> 59:14.547
Don't tell anyone
about what I said.

59:14.619 --> 59:17.179
Sure.

59:19.290 --> 59:21.987
<i>60 seconds to VTR.
Two minutes, live.</i>

59:22.059 --> 59:23.549
The Yankees win
the World Series.

59:23.628 --> 59:25.619
That was a big shock
after they won 114 games.

59:25.696 --> 59:28.597
What is it with this element of
surprise you people are looking for?

59:28.666 --> 59:30.191
You know
what we're forgetting?

59:30.268 --> 59:33.363
-- What? -- Michael Jordan and the
Bulls win the NBA championship.

59:33.437 --> 59:34.927
Yeah, there's something
that doesn't happen a lot.

59:35.006 --> 59:36.405
What do you guys think?

59:36.474 --> 59:38.602
-- <i>Us?</i>
-- <i>Yeah, what do you think?</i>

59:38.676 --> 59:39.700
-- About <i>what?</i>
-- <i>Play of the year.</i>

59:39.777 --> 59:40.938
We're eight days away.

59:41.012 --> 59:42.673
-- I hadn't really --
-- What <i>do</i> you think?

59:42.747 --> 59:44.476
We're studio technicians.

59:44.549 --> 59:46.677
<i>-- Yes' we know. -- These
are editorial questions.</i>

59:46.751 --> 59:48.344
Yes, we want to hear
what you have to say.

59:48.419 --> 59:50.717
-- Really? -- Go ahead.
There are no wrong answers.

59:50.788 --> 59:52.381
Nothing's too stupid
to suggest.

59:52.456 --> 59:55.426
Except women's ice hockey, but Kim
pretty much has that covered.

59:55.493 --> 59:56.551
So what do you think?

59:56.627 --> 59:58.527
-- You really want to know?
-- <i>Absolutely.</i>

59:58.596 --> 01:00:00.291
Mark O'Meara
winning two majors.

01:00:00.364 --> 01:00:02.628
-- Cal Ripken ending the streak.
-- Peyton Manning.

01:00:02.700 --> 01:00:05.465
Well, that was a colossal
waste of time.

01:00:06.871 --> 01:00:07.804
Good evening.

01:00:07.872 --> 01:00:09.897
Isaac, I haven't
seen you all night.

01:00:09.974 --> 01:00:12.671
Dana, I hate to do this
to you on such short notice,

01:00:12.743 --> 01:00:15.610
but I'd like a couple of
minutes of airtime tonight.

01:00:15.680 --> 01:00:18.081
-- Really? -- If you
need to make some room,

01:00:18.149 --> 01:00:20.811
I believe you can dump that piece
that Danny was planning on doing.

01:00:20.885 --> 01:00:22.649
I don't think he'll mind.

01:00:22.720 --> 01:00:24.882
No, I don't believe
he will.

01:00:24.956 --> 01:00:26.822
He said something to
you, didn't he?

01:00:26.891 --> 01:00:29.292
Will...

01:00:29.360 --> 01:00:30.794
get Isaac wired up.

01:00:30.862 --> 01:00:32.523
Sure.

01:00:36.267 --> 01:00:38.634
Earlier in the show, we told
you about Roland Shepard

01:00:38.703 --> 01:00:41.229
and the six other players who
were dropped from their team

01:00:41.305 --> 01:00:44.639
and then their school for refusing to
play football under the Confederate flag.

01:00:44.709 --> 01:00:47.974
Here's Isaac Jaffee, managing
editor of “Sports Night,“

01:00:48.045 --> 01:00:50.139
with an editorial
comment. Isaac?

01:00:50.248 --> 01:00:52.239
Thank you, Casey.

01:00:52.283 --> 01:00:55.981
<i>Exaudio, comperio,
conloquor.</i>

01:00:56.053 --> 01:00:58.681
That's a Latin phrase
that translates...

01:00:58.756 --> 01:01:01.953
"To listen, to learn,
to speak."

01:01:02.026 --> 01:01:04.495
Those words are carved
into the stone arches

01:01:04.562 --> 01:01:07.327
that form the entrance to
the undergraduate library

01:01:07.398 --> 01:01:09.298
at Tennessee
Western University.

01:01:09.367 --> 01:01:12.894
This afternoon, an extraordinary
young man named Roland Shepard

01:01:12.970 --> 01:01:17.134
made what had to have been
an excruciating decision.

01:01:17.208 --> 01:01:21.145
He said he wasn't playing football
under a Confederate flag.

01:01:21.212 --> 01:01:25.274
Six of his teammates then chose
not to let Shepard stand alone.

01:01:25.349 --> 01:01:27.977
And I choose to join them
at this moment.

01:01:28.052 --> 01:01:31.454
In the history of the South,
there's much to celebrate.

01:01:31.522 --> 01:01:34.389
And that flag is
a desecration of all of it.

01:01:34.458 --> 01:01:36.927
It's a banner of hatred
and separatism.

01:01:36.994 --> 01:01:39.463
It's a banner of
ignorance and violence

01:01:39.530 --> 01:01:42.363
and a war that pitted
brother against brother,

01:01:42.433 --> 01:01:45.061
and to ask young
black men and women,

01:01:45.136 --> 01:01:48.629
<i>young Jewish men and women,
Asians, Native Americans,</i>

01:01:48.706 --> 01:01:51.471
to ask Americans to walk
beneath its shadow

01:01:51.542 --> 01:01:54.512
is a humiliation
of irreducible proportions.

01:01:54.578 --> 01:01:55.875
And we all know it.

01:01:55.947 --> 01:01:58.211
<i>Tennessee Western
has produced</i>

01:01:58.282 --> 01:02:00.649
<i>some outstanding alumni
in the last hundred years,</i>

01:02:00.718 --> 01:02:04.154
people of wisdom and vision,
strength and compassion.

01:02:04.221 --> 01:02:06.246
One of them is Luther Sachs.

01:02:06.324 --> 01:02:08.258
Luther Sachs owns
Continental Corp,

01:02:08.326 --> 01:02:10.226
which owns the
Continental Sports Channel,

01:02:10.294 --> 01:02:12.388
which you're watching
right now.

01:02:12.463 --> 01:02:16.661
<i>Luther Sachs is a generous alumni
contributor to Tennessee Western</i>

01:02:16.734 --> 01:02:18.725
<i>with a considerable influence</i>

01:02:18.803 --> 01:02:21.272
over its chancellor,
Davis Blake,

01:02:21.339 --> 01:02:23.137
and its board of trustees.

01:02:23.207 --> 01:02:26.939
Luther, you've got
a phone call to make.

01:02:28.145 --> 01:02:30.170
<i>You've got to call
Chancellor Blake</i>

01:02:30.247 --> 01:02:33.046
<i>and tell him
to take down that flag</i>

01:02:33.117 --> 01:02:36.087
or he can stop looking
for your checks in the mail.

01:02:36.153 --> 01:02:40.420
You've got to put these young men back
in a classroom, and I mean pronto.

01:02:40.491 --> 01:02:43.552
These boys are gonna make you
proud one day, Luther.

01:02:43.627 --> 01:02:46.858
<i>I challenge you
to do the right thing</i> --

01:02:46.931 --> 01:02:48.399
not an unreasonable request

01:02:48.466 --> 01:02:50.901
to make of a man
whose alma mater declares,

01:02:50.968 --> 01:02:54.962
"Exaudio, comperio,
conloquor" --

01:02:55.039 --> 01:02:59.476
to listen, to learn,
to speak.

01:02:59.543 --> 01:03:02.945
In the meantime, God go
with you, Roland Shepard,

01:03:03.014 --> 01:03:06.882
and you six Southern
gentlemen of Tennessee.

01:03:06.951 --> 01:03:10.785
God's not done
with any of you yet.

01:03:12.857 --> 01:03:16.293
That was our managing
editor, Isaac Jaffee.

01:03:16.360 --> 01:03:17.623
We'll be back.

01:03:17.695 --> 01:03:19.754
<i>We're out.</i>

01:03:19.830 --> 01:03:20.763
[Applause]

01:03:20.831 --> 01:03:22.458
You can bring it, boss.

01:03:23.667 --> 01:03:25.795
You know I could kiss you on
the mouth right now, right?

01:03:25.870 --> 01:03:28.168
[Laughs]
Then stay over there.

01:03:28.239 --> 01:03:30.435
I could get very physical
with you right now.

01:03:30.508 --> 01:03:32.408
Danny...

01:03:32.476 --> 01:03:34.274
I'm having some
very kooky thoughts here.

01:03:34.345 --> 01:03:37.679
[indistinct talking]

01:03:41.886 --> 01:03:44.014
-- Thank you all.
-- Isaac...

01:03:44.088 --> 01:03:46.182
I can't even --
that was...

01:03:46.257 --> 01:03:47.816
-- I-| mean...
-- All right!

01:03:47.892 --> 01:03:50.156
We've lost radio contact
with Dana.

01:03:50.261 --> 01:03:51.228
[Laughter]

01:03:51.262 --> 01:03:52.696
-- <i>Isaac...</i>
-- <i>Yes?</i>

01:03:52.763 --> 01:03:54.959
No kidding --
play of the year.

01:03:55.032 --> 01:03:56.363
Thank you, Jeremy.

01:03:56.434 --> 01:03:58.425
Isaac?

01:03:58.502 --> 01:04:00.300
Showtime?

01:04:00.371 --> 01:04:02.499
Luther Sachs on line 4.

01:04:06.510 --> 01:04:08.376
Hey, Isaac...

01:04:08.446 --> 01:04:10.471
<i>Yes;?</i>

01:04:10.548 --> 01:04:13.609
Right behind ya.

01:04:13.684 --> 01:04:15.277
<i>Back in 10.</i>

01:04:15.352 --> 01:04:17.548
It was -- I've never...

01:04:17.621 --> 01:04:18.679
<i>[Sighs]</i>

01:04:18.756 --> 01:04:21.020
I mean, I'm serious.
That was just...

01:04:21.092 --> 01:04:23.356
In 3...2...

01:04:23.427 --> 01:04:25.828
That's all for tonight,
but before we sign off,

01:04:25.896 --> 01:04:27.921
we felt that with Christmas
only a few days off

01:04:27.998 --> 01:04:30.490
and with people making up lists
and checking them twice,

01:04:30.568 --> 01:04:33.003
it was as good a time as
any to mention some people

01:04:33.070 --> 01:04:35.664
who are important to us
here at the show.

01:04:35.739 --> 01:04:37.332
It seems that quite
a few of you, for instance,

01:04:37.408 --> 01:04:38.807
like the way Dan and I
dress on the air,

01:04:38.876 --> 01:04:40.844
and you should know
that we're dressed

01:04:40.911 --> 01:04:43.403
by Maureen Gates
and Joseph Roveto.

01:04:43.481 --> 01:04:46.712
Maureen and Joseph are assisted by a
young woman named Monica Brazelton,

01:04:46.784 --> 01:04:48.912
<i>and Monica is not
to be trifled with.</i>

01:04:48.986 --> 01:04:50.852
Our camera operators
are Ray,

01:04:50.921 --> 01:04:52.980
Wayne, Bruce,
John, and Jerome,

01:04:53.057 --> 01:04:55.116
who wishes we'd do
more features on hockey.

01:04:55.192 --> 01:04:56.421
Not gonna happen, Jerome.

01:04:56.494 --> 01:04:59.191
Every time I pick up a pencil
or put down a coffee mug,

01:04:59.263 --> 01:05:01.493
that's Jody Mann and her
trusty aid John Frantz,

01:05:01.565 --> 01:05:04.660
and if you've ever wondered what
a gaffer was or a best boy,

01:05:04.735 --> 01:05:06.260
you should ask
Keith and Mark.

01:05:06.337 --> 01:05:07.896
We've got some people
who don't get paid much,

01:05:07.972 --> 01:05:09.565
but that's okay, 'cause
the hours are terrible.

01:05:09.640 --> 01:05:11.608
They're our P.A.s,
and their names are

01:05:11.675 --> 01:05:14.610
Lauren, Victoria, Jake,
Lee, Ashley, and Brad.

01:05:14.678 --> 01:05:16.578
This is a script.
Dan and I write it.

01:05:16.647 --> 01:05:19.673
And then two people come along and put
it together so that we can also read it.

01:05:19.750 --> 01:05:21.149
Their names are
Joan and Chris,

01:05:21.218 --> 01:05:23.186
and they, us, and everyone
else here are pretty much

01:05:23.254 --> 01:05:25.518
at the mercy of the script
supervisor, Carol MoKechnie,

01:05:25.589 --> 01:05:28.354
who's got a little thing for me, and
I think it's time she admits it.

01:05:28.425 --> 01:05:29.620
-- Keri McIntyre...
-- Nicole Burke...

01:05:29.693 --> 01:05:31.252
-- <i>Shawn Hanley...</i>
-- <i>Jeff Wheat...</i>

01:05:31.328 --> 01:05:32.454
-- Mark Johnson...
-- Cajun...

01:05:32.530 --> 01:05:34.225
-- <i>Cajun...</i>
-- <i>How 'bout Skip Cook?</i>

01:05:34.298 --> 01:05:37.097
-- <i>How 'bout Phil</i> Heath? -- <i>How 'bout
Karen, Julie, and Angela in makeup?</i>

01:05:37.168 --> 01:05:38.863
How 'bout Brenda,
Cammy, and Jody in hair?

01:05:38.936 --> 01:05:41.371
We've got film on this show.
You know who cuts it?

01:05:41.438 --> 01:05:43.099
Janet Ashikaga.
Know who her assistant is?

01:05:43.174 --> 01:05:44.938
Laura the wonderful.

01:05:45.009 --> 01:05:46.875
We've just named a small
fraction of the people

01:05:46.944 --> 01:05:48.207
who put
this show on television,

01:05:48.279 --> 01:05:50.008
which means we've
left out many more,

01:05:50.114 --> 01:05:53.049
and we'll try and rectify that as
we head towards December 25th.

01:05:53.083 --> 01:05:56.485
But for now, I'm Casey
McCall alongside Dan Rydell

01:05:56.554 --> 01:05:58.579
wishing everyone
in your home,

01:05:58.656 --> 01:06:00.988
along with everyone
here at my home,

01:06:01.058 --> 01:06:02.787
a very happy Christmas.

01:06:02.860 --> 01:06:04.521
Good night, everyone.

01:06:16.273 --> 01:06:18.970
[Rock music plays]
